The Graph Explore API does not work when using an index pattern that contains a wildcard that matches the datastream (not the actual backing indexes!).

Steps to reproduce:

- Follow our [Set up a data stream documentation](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/set-up-a-data-stream.html) step by step till step 4 (step 5+ are not required).
- You should now have a datastream called `my-data-stream` filled with data.
- You can search fine over that datastream with either of those: `GET /my-data-stream/_search` or `GET /my-data-stream*/_search`

But in the `_graph/explore` API the latter one (with wildcard) does simply fail with an `index_not_found`.

The following request will work fine (albeit not making much sense):

```
GET my-data-stream/_graph/explore
{
  "query": {
    "match": {
      "@timestamp": "2099-05-06T16:21:15.000Z"
    }
  },
  "vertices": [
    { "field": "message" }
  ],
  "connections": {
    "vertices": [
      {"field": "message" }
    ]
  }
}
```

Sending the following query though will result in the error below:

```
GET my-data-stream*/_graph/explore
{
  "query": {
    "match": {
      "@timestamp": "2099-05-06T16:21:15.000Z"
    }
  },
  "vertices": [
    { "field": "message" }
  ],
  "connections": {
    "vertices": [
      {"field": "message" }
    ]
  }
}
```

```
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [
      {
        "type" : "index_not_found_exception",
        "reason" : "no such index [my-data-stream*]",
        "index_uuid" : "_na_",
        "index" : "my-data-stream*"
      }
    ],
    "type" : "index_not_found_exception",
    "reason" : "no such index [my-data-stream*]",
    "index_uuid" : "_na_",
    "index" : "my-data-stream*"
  },
  "status" : 404
}
```

**Expected behavior:** `my-data-stream*` should work the same fine with the `_graph/explore` API than it does with the `_search` API.

This is currently affecting Kibana users using the Graph application, and often access the data stream via that wildcard index pattern (I believe even some of our beats modules, etc. are creating the index patterns like that).

**Elasticsearch version** (`bin/elasticsearch --version`): master/7.x

**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:

The `PointInTimeBuilder` takes a `TimeValue` as an argument for the keepalive time. Serializing to JSON works fine, however parsing a timevalue back, that is not based on full minutes is an issue.

**Steps to reproduce**:

Either via dev-tools

```
POST /my-index-000001/_pit?keep_alive=1.1m
```

or via a Java test

```java
public class PointInTimeBuilderTests extends ESTestCase {

    public void testKeepAlivePit() throws Exception {
        final PointInTimeBuilder builder = new PointInTimeBuilder("my_pit_it");
        builder.setKeepAlive(TimeValue.timeValueSeconds(66));

        byte[] data;
        try (XContentBuilder xContentBuilder = jsonBuilder()) {
            xContentBuilder.startObject();
            builder.toXContent(xContentBuilder, ToXContent.EMPTY_PARAMS);
            xContentBuilder.endObject();
            xContentBuilder.flush();
            data = ((ByteArrayOutputStream) xContentBuilder.getOutputStream()).toByteArray();
        }

        // now parse again
        try (XContentParser parser = XContentFactory.xContent(XContentType.JSON)
                .createParser(NamedXContentRegistry.EMPTY, LoggingDeprecationHandler.INSTANCE, data)) {
            parser.nextToken();
            parser.nextToken();
            PointInTimeBuilder.fromXContent(parser);
        }
    }
}
```

This snippet fails with

```
Caused by: java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: failed to parse [1.1m], fractional time values are not supported
	at org.elasticsearch.core.TimeValue.parse(TimeValue.java:392)
	at org.elasticsearch.core.TimeValue.parseTimeValue(TimeValue.java:363)
	at org.elasticsearch.core.TimeValue.parseTimeValue(TimeValue.java:344)
	at org.elasticsearch.search.builder.PointInTimeBuilder.lambda$static$3(PointInTimeBuilder.java:40)
	at org.elasticsearch.common.xcontent.ObjectParser.lambda$declareField$11(ObjectParser.java:398)
	at org.elasticsearch.common.xcontent.ObjectParser.parseValue(ObjectParser.java:541)
	... 42 more
```

The time value serializes this out to `1.1m` but cannot serialize this back.

When creating an alias from an action that uses a wildcard expression in `indices` field that matches with a data stream via the update aliases api then an error occurs instead of creating the alias.

Note that error doesn't occur if a concrete data stream name is used in the `indices` field of an alias action.

Reproduction:

```
PUT /_data_stream/logs-foo-bar

GET /_cat/indices

POST /_aliases
{
    "actions": [
        {
            "add": {
                "indices": ["logs-foo-* "],
                "aliases": ["my-alias"]
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

